2019 Sept 08 : After a daylight recording session I saw a male Andean Duck hitting his inflated chest with the bill and sang this pitch.


First Impression: I identified the species as a Lake Duck (Oxyura vittata) because I watched it by his silhouette and it's the regular Oxyura duck on this spot. On winter seasons is probably to has sightings of Andean duck but I compared with the [Bernabe's recording] <https://www.xeno-canto.org/44471>which one is different than the recorded calls.

natural vocalizations; calls from one of a pair at extremely close range along a stream moving through boggy ground above treeline.  Calls from the other of the pair audible in the background.  This pair had a pair of very young chicks so these calls were probably given in alarm to my presence, though the bird was mostly foraging without appearing alarmed.

natural vocalizations; song? from one bird displaying to another.  This pair had two very young chicks, and these could be alarm calls, but the behavior suggest otherwise.  While giving these calls, the bird calling stood up taller and straighter than usual, and walked a tight circle around the second bird (which can be heard giving some quiet calls in the background of this cut).  I heard this exchange three times, and the other two were longer (6-7 notes), but this is the only one I could get on tape.  These birds were in boggy ground along a small stream above timberline.
